“In the Republic of Congo recent studies show that the number of young girls getting married has increased whereas divorce these last years was a taboo at the national level, and that despite the rumors about its increasing irregular use,” explained Minvielle.

In the absence of national data on divorce, the principle that “if one spouse wants a divorce then the relationship is considered as separated” was used to classify separation. This definition does not illustrate men’s perspectives on the matter.

“Nine young men recognize to have gotten a divorce because their wives got pregnant as minors. Women’s pregnancies play a decisive role in the decision of men for divorce,” said Minvielle.

In fact, four lines of disagreement make divorce a frightening prospect for women in the pilot communities: uncertainty about living standards after marriage, children’s future, the position of social standing as well as social acceptance, primarily by in-laws and husbands’ relatives. “Many women define ‘becoming a widow’ as something shameful,” said Minvielle.
